    "28988364": {
      "title": "The ultrastructure of fluorosed human dental enamel",
      "abstract": "— More than 80 specimens of enamel from 20 ground sections of eight teeth showing severe dental fluorosis have been examined in the transmission electron microscope. The study has shown that the prisms have normal size and form, but are surrounded by large periprismatic gaps. The individual crystals commonly appear in cross sections as regular, flattened hexagons with an average width of 91 nm and average thickness of 45 nm. Particularly in the tail regions and at prism peripheries, extensive intercrystalline spaces were found. The crystal lattice demonstrated a spacing of 0.82 nm. Demineralization of thin sections with PTA showed a preferential dissolution of the crystal centers. Based on the ultra-structural observations it is proposed that the hypomineralized regions of fluorosed enamel are produced by an arrest of enamel maturation, possibly due to toxic damage to the ameloblasts in the absorptive or maturative phase of their life cycle."
    }
  },
